<article>
    <h1>Eye&#xAD;ing re&#xAD;gional trade for eco&#xAD;nomic re&#xAD;newal</h1>
    <h2>Asia News Net&#xAD;work writ&#xAD;ers re&#xAD;view the out&#xAD;look and po&#xAD;ten&#xAD;tial of re&#xAD;gional trade pacts. Here are ex&#xAD;cerpts.</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20210109/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2021-01-09"><time>2021-01-09</time></a>
        - <span>NEWS FOCUS ASIAN INSIDER</span>
        - <span role="byline">Ed&#xAD;i&#xAD;to&#xAD;rial&#xD;&#xA;China Daily, China</span>
    </section>

    <p>Ac­cel­er­ate East Asia trade</p>
    <p>De­spite the chal­lenges pre­sented by the global public health cri­sis and anti-glob­al­i­sa­tion head­winds, there are in­creas­ing ex­pec­ta­tions that China, Ja­pan and South Korea will sign an ad­vanced free trade agree­ment (FTA).</p>
    <p>As mem­bers of the re­cently inked Re­gional Com­pre­hen­sive Eco­nomic Part­ner­ship (RCEP) agree­ment, the three coun­tries lay an im­por­tant foun­da­tion for an FTA, which, if con­cluded, will be­come a new en­gine for Asia-Pa­cific eco­nomic in­te­gra­tion and the re­cov­ery of the global econ­omy.</p>
    <p>The in­dus­tries of China, Ja­pan and South Korea are highly com­ple­men­tary and their tri­lat­eral trade vol­ume has in­creased from US$132 bil­lion (S$174.76 bil­lion) in 1999 to US$622 bil­lion in 2019, up 370 per cent in 20 years.</p>
    <p>Their economies ac­count for 70 per cent of the Asian econ­omy and 20 per cent of the world econ­omy and, along with China and Ja­pan, South Korea is ex­pected to be among the world’s 10 largest economies this year.</p>
    <p>How­ever, trade among the three ac­counts for just 23 per cent of their to­tal trade, much lower than the 65 per cent trade among mem­bers of the Euro­pean Union and the 40 per cent among economies in the United States-Mex­ico-Canada Agree­ment.</p>
    <p>While the coro­n­avirus pan­demic has led to the con­trac­tion of global in­dus­trial and sup­ply chains, the nat­u­ral ge­o­graph­i­cal, in­dus­trial and eco­nomic ad­van­tages shared by China, Ja­pan and South Korea have helped ac­cel­er­ate the in­te­gra­tion of their in­dus­trial and sup­ply chains.</p>
    <p>The three coun­tries should not only strengthen eco­nomic co­op­er­a­tion and push for the con­clu­sion of an ad­vanced tri­lat­eral FTA, but also in­crease mu­tual trust so that they can work closely in mul­ti­lat­eral or­gan­i­sa­tions such as the World Trade Or­gan­i­sa­tion.</p>
    <p>This will not only help re­duce trans­ac­tion costs and pro­mote eco­nomic in­te­gra­tion in East Asia, but also con­trib­ute to eco­nomic re­cov­ery in the Asia-Pa­cific, re­store the world trade or­der, and make the three economies the sta­bilis­ers and en­gines of world eco­nomic growth.</p>


</article>

